{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507865"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2679"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2679"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.12,0.08,0.02,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41924"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2679"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26904"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44946"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41924"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 87-year-old man presents with a three month history of progressive confusion. Nursing staff from his residential facility mention that he has been increasingly withdrawn. He has a medical history of Parkinson\u0027s disease, stroke, and hearing loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has normal vital signs. He has hearing aids in both ears. After removal of the hearing aids, Weber\u0027s test lateralises to the left. His Rinne test showed air conduction greater than bone conduction on the right and bone conduction better than air conduction on the left. Cranial nerve examination is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bilateral presbycusis - worse on the left side","Left-sided acoustic neuroma","Right-sided osteosclerosis","Chronic serous otitis media - worse on the right side","Left conductive hearing loss"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has Weber\u0027s test that lateralises to the left which could be due to a conductive hearing loss on the left or a sensorineural hearing loss on the right. The key to this question is that the Rinne test on the left shows bone conduction is better than air conduction on this side. Taking both tests together this would indicate a conductive hearing loss on the left with pathology either in the external ear (wax, foreign body, collapsing ear canal, otitis externa) or middle ear - fluid, subtotal tympanic membrane perforation, otosclerosis or middle ear fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote that with mild-conductive hearing loss (\u0026lt;30 dB), a lateralising Weber test may exist in the presence of air conduction being greater than bone conduction (Rinne\u0027s positive). This can occur with incomplete occlusion of the external auditory canal by wax or cartilaginous collapse that can occur with age. Moderate to severe conductive hearing loss (\u0026gt;30dB) typically also manifests with bone conduction greater than air conduction in addition to the lateralizing Weber test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPresbycusis is a condition that causes sensorineural hearing loss; thus, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebilateral presbycusis worse on the left side\u003C/strong\u003E would cause Weber\u0027s test to lateralise to the right, not the left.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft-sided acoustic neuroma \u003C/strong\u003Ewould cause a sensorineural hearing loss on the left side. This would cause Weber\u0027s test to lateralise to the right, not the left.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight-sided osteosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a cause of conductive hearing loss. As a result, it would cause Weber\u0027s test to lateralise to the right, and would also potentially cause bone conduction to be greater than air conduction on the right.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic serous otitis media\u003C/strong\u003E would cause conductive hearing loss; and therefore, if this was \u003Cstrong\u003Eworse on the left side\u003C/strong\u003E, this would cause Weber\u0027s test to lateralise to the left.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mild conductive hearing loss does not cause Rinne\u0027s test (bone conduction greater than air conduction) to be negative."],"references":["Kelly EA et al. Diagnostic accuracy of tuning fork tests for hearing loss: a systematic review. Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg 2018 Aug; 159:220.","Shaikh N et al. Videos in clinical medicine. Diagnosing otitis media--otoscopy and cerumen removal. N Engl J Med 2010 May 21; 362:e62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26904"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2679"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26904"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-27T14:16:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-27T14:16:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2679"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41924"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"O